"Debusschere V., Multon B., Ben Ahmed H., Cavarec P.E.","Life cycle design of a single-phase induction motor",2010,"IET Electric Power Applications","4","5", IEPAAN000004000005000348000001,"348","356",,,10.1049/iet-epa.2009.0173,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953492942&partnerID=40&md5=fa1029bacd01a92c0242423028ecc63a","SATIE, ENS Cachan Bretagne, CNRS, UEB, av. Robert. Schuman, F35170 Bruz, France; TandE SOMFY SAS, 400 av. de la Re publique, 74307 Cluses, France","Debusschere, V., SATIE, ENS Cachan Bretagne, CNRS, UEB, av. Robert. Schuman, F35170 Bruz, France; Multon, B., SATIE, ENS Cachan Bretagne, CNRS, UEB, av. Robert. Schuman, F35170 Bruz, France; Ben Ahmed, H., SATIE, ENS Cachan Bretagne, CNRS, UEB, av. Robert. Schuman, F35170 Bruz, France; Cavarec, P.E., TandE SOMFY SAS, 400 av. de la Re publique, 74307 Cluses, France","This study focuses on the optimisation of a single-phase permanent capacitor induction machine with respect to two environmental criteria: gross energy requirement and global warming potential. The study presented has been applied to roller shutter drives; these motors display a low ratio value of cumulative operating time to total lifetime. Since the studied motors are placed in roller shutter tubes, whose diameter has been fixed because of production and distribution constraints, only two free parameters are available as part of our optimisation routine: the active length and number of turns per phase. The short operating times of these motors necessitate a transient thermal modelling approach. Based on the typical operating cycle of a roller shutter, the authors have emphasised the impact of production and transport stages on our optimisation results. Minimising operating losses or maximising operating efficiency are not valid criteria for this particular application. So a new efficiency is introduced: the life-cycle efficiency. Gross energy requirement and global warming potential are the main optimisation criteria whereas active length and turn number are the main sizing parameters available in this study. Sensitivity analyses have also been conducted on: the operating cycle, cage and winding materials, and the energy mix. © 2010 The Institution of Engineering and Technology.",,"Cumulative operating time; Energy mix; Energy requirements; Free parameters; Global warming potential; Induction machines; Life-cycle design; Operating cycle; Operating efficiency; Operating loss; Optimisations; Single phase induction motor; Thermal modelling; Global warming; Induction motors; Life cycle; Rollers (machine components); Sensitivity analysis; Optimization",,,,,,"Environmental management systems - requirements with guidance for use http://www.iso.org/iso/iso_catalogue/catalogue_tc/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=31807, (International Organization for Standardization, Geneva, Switzerland, 1st Ed. 2004, Last ed. 2009), http://www.iso.org/iso/iso_catalogue/catalogue_tc/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=31807, accessed January 2010Jolliet, O., Saade, M., Crettaz, P., Analyse du Cycle de Vie. Comprendre et réaliser un écobilan (Life cycle assessment. Understand and practice ecobilan, in French) (2005), Presses Polytechniques Universitaires RomandesUdo de Haes, A., Van Rooijen, M., Life cycle approaches - the road from analysis to practice (2005), UNEP/SETAC Life Cycle InitiativeJardini, J.A., Tahan, C.M.V., Ferrari, E.L., Ahn, S.U., Selection of distribution transformer based on economic criteria (1997) Int. Conf. on Exhibition on Electricity Distribution, pp. 141-145. , Birmingham, UK, June; Tukker, A., Eder, P., Charter, M., Haag, E., Vercalsteren, A., Wiedmann, T., Eco-design: the state of implementation in Europe - conclusions of a state of the art study for IPTS (2001) J. Sustainable Prod. Des., 1 (3), pp. 147-161; Convers, J.F., Tran, T.V., Brisset, S., Andries, V., Bekermans, M., Brochet, P., EcoDesign of an auxiliary transformer for the railway traction (2008) Int. Conf. on Exhibition on Ecol